<br>
Honestly, there is nothing that an officer in this guild *does* that a normal member shouldn't be able to do.  AoL doesn't lead raids, or go on major raids, so there's no need for an officer there.  When it comes to a person getting &quot;out of hand&quot;, how do you say having an &quot;officer&quot; is better?  Who says the officer is going to do the right thing?  That's something that the guild in itself should work toward- perfecting its members.  What happens if you call a member a name?  Not near as worse, I garuntee, as if you call an officer one.<br>
<br>
Honestly, you're just taking more powers away from members and giving them to officers, which makes it worse to be in your guild.  There's no real need to have an officer in your guild, because every power they have another person could have.  <br>
<br>
As I told Del, if you want to show someone has been around for a while, then why don't you say &quot;elder member.&quot;  The way the system is set up now, officers are more important than a common member, for no real reason at all.  Elder members might be, yes, but only because they've been around for a while.  <br>
<br>
I guess I honestly see no reason in having an officer in a guild that doesn't go on specific raids except to show some people are more important than others.  <br>
