<br>
Let me paint a picture for you with YOUR example as given. You say that raids need officers. So you have a group of people brought together for a specific goal. You have a large amount of people, be they experienced, elder, or in-experienced people. Now, to accomplish this goal you have a Raid leader, along with Group Leaders. In any common raid the attendants will speak through their group leader to the Raid Leader. Follow me? Now think of a guild as a raid. Our purpose is to play the game per say. We have a raid leader (Guild Leader) and group leaders (Officers) to help accomplish this task. Seem a little clearer?<br>
<br>
Now on &quot;Elder Members&quot;. Are you saying that by one person playing longer than another he/she should have or does have more knowledge of the game? Not to mention do they have the ability and/or play style to effectively lead a group of players? What about the person who has played for three years, but never experienced the game above level 45? Does he/she have a leg up on the player who has played for a year and has two 60+ characters? In my opinion it is &quot;player based&quot;. What YOU as a player can offer the game, not how much TIME you spend on the game. Or does play time distinguish these Elder Members? Does one have to constantly play in order to be given this title?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Honestly, you're just taking more powers away from members and giving them to officers, which makes it worse to be in your guild. There's no real need to have an officer in your guild, because every power they have another person could have.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
